author: @nut2616
text: One tip, a great way to get massive data sets is using google's search API (pip install google, import googlesearch) and then use requests to get the HTML data from every website returned by that search up to 10,000 pages. So for example,    from googlesearch import search import requests  for x in tuple(search('cats'))[:10000]:    print(requests.get(x).text)   However, google searching too quickly will have google shut you down. Also, your computer may need a breather every time a webpage is accessed so use time.sleep() when necessary

author: @5zazen
text: This was an interesting presentation.  Neural networks are likely not as fragile as biological neural networks.  Initial learning is due to chemical synaptic changes and over time dendritic changes and actual new wiring is put down. Problems can be many due to dopamine/catecholamine excess/deficiencies, and learning takes time to consolidate during sleep which is required largely due to overload, or inhibition, after a person has been awake for a day.  Sleep allows information processing.  Also, there are many different types of learning involving different procedures, brain areas, due to information type and body involvement, eg, declarative vs procedural.  With computers, AI, these inhibitions are zero.  No sleep, no synapses, just electricity and 0 and 1.  As Google showed with Go, associations can be made.  This combined with brute force speed of many cpus is amazing.  Think Skynet.  Its coming.
